In this article, President Barack Obama proclaims May 5, 2011, as a National Day of Prayer. He highlights the importance of prayer in American history and the role it has played in shaping the nation's leaders. Obama mentions President Abraham Lincoln and his reliance on prayer during difficult times. He also references Coretta Scott King's account of her husband, Dr. Martin Luther King Jr., praying for guidance during the civil rights movement. The President encourages citizens to be thankful for the freedom of religious expression and other blessings. He urges prayers for the military, first responders, and those affected by natural disasters. Obama also asks for prayers for people around the world seeking peace and justice. The proclamation is in accordance with Public Law 100-307, which designates the first Thursday in May as the National Day of Prayer.